</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1016/j.jtocrr.2022.100347</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9257415</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35815322</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41294688</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>28</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1718-7729</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>32</Volume><Issue>11</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Nov</Month><Day>06</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Current oncology (Toronto, Ont.)</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Curr Oncol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Evolving Therapeutic Landscape of ROS1-Positive Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer: An Updated Review.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">626</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3390/curroncol32110626</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText><i>ROS1</i> gene rearrangements define a distinct molecular subtype of non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC), occurring in approximately 2% of cases and frequently associated with younger age, non-smoker status, and a high incidence of brain metastases. The discovery of ROS1 as an oncogenic driver has led to the development of targeted tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs). Crizotinib first demonstrated substantial clinical benefit, but its limitations, including poor central nervous system (CNS) penetration and acquired resistance, highlighted the need for next-generation inhibitors. Several agents have since been developed, including entrectinib, lorlatinib, repotrectinib, taletrectinib, and zidesamtinib, each offering improved intracranial (IC) activity and efficacy against resistance mutations, notably <i>ROS1^G2032R</i>. Despite these advances, optimal sequencing strategies remain undefined, and resistance ultimately emerges in most patients. This review provides an updated overview of ROS1 biology, diagnostic approaches, clinical outcomes with currently available TKIs, mechanisms of resistance, and ongoing challenges, emphasizing the rapidly evolving therapeutic landscape.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bischoff</LastName><ForeName>Herv&#xe9;</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-3382-9635</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strasbourg Europe, F-67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gendarme</LastName><ForeName>S&#xe9;bastien</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Service de Pneumologie, H&#xf4;pital Tenon, APHP, Inserm U955, IMRB, Universit&#xe9; Paris-Est Cr&#xe9;teil, F-94010 Cr&#xe9;teil, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Somme</LastName><ForeName>Laura</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-3486-8505</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strasbourg Europe, F-67200 Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Chouaid</LastName><ForeName>Christos</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-4290-5524</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Centre de Recherche Clinique, CHI Cr&#xe9;teil, Inserm U955, IMRB, Universit&#xe9; Paris-Est Cr&#xe9;teil, F-94010 Cr&#xe9;teil, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Schott</LastName><ForeName>Roland</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-7735-5366</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Medical Oncology, Institut de Canc&#xe9;rologie Strasbo